# PCONFIG (Peripheral Configuration Library) Configuration

menuconfig PCONFIG
	bool "PCONFIG (Peripheral Configuration Library)"
	default n
	depends on OSAL
	help
	  Peripheral Configuration Library provides read-only access to
	  product-defined hardware configuration tables.

	  PCONFIG describes the physical hardware configuration of a platform
	  (board variant, peripheral connections, pin mappings, etc.) in a
	  structured, data-driven way.

	  Key features:
	  - Platform-specific hardware descriptions
	  - Board variant tables compiled in by the product
	  - Peripheral configuration tables
	  - Query-only platform configuration API

	  Memory footprint: small code footprint + product configuration data

	  Use cases:
	  - Fixed product hardware descriptions
	  - Multi-board product variants selected at build time
	  - Hardware abstraction for applications and PDL
	  - Peripheral lookup by index or platform/product name

	  Dependencies: OSAL (for basic services)

	  Note: Enable OSAL first in "Core Modules" menu.
	  Runtime code must not register, reload, switch, or mutate PCONFIG data
	  through core APIs.

	  Recommended: Enable for products with hardware configuration tables

	  If unsure, say Y.

if PCONFIG

menu "PCONFIG Build Configuration"

config PCONFIG_BUILD_STATIC
	bool "Build static library (.a)"
	default n
	help
	  Build PCONFIG as a static library (libpconfig.a).

	  Static linking advantages:
	  - No runtime dependencies
	  - Configuration data embedded in executable
	  - Slightly faster (no dynamic linking)

	  Recommended: Enable for embedded systems with fixed hardware

config PCONFIG_BUILD_SHARED
	bool "Build shared library (.so)"
	default n
	help
	  Build PCONFIG as a shared library (libpconfig.so).

	  Shared library advantages:
	  - Smaller executable size
	  - Code sharing between processes

	  Note: configuration data is still read-only from PCONFIG's public API.

	  Recommended: Enable for multi-application systems

endmenu

endif # PCONFIG
